    sunPara: `Colorado Springs averages 5.2-5.6 peak sun hours per day at 6,035 feet elevation with 243 sunny days. The high altitude enhances ground-level irradiance by 15-18% versus sea-level markets at the same latitude because the thinner atmosphere absorbs less solar radiation. However, the altitude also reduces panel output through a less-discussed mechanism: the lower air density provides 18% less convective cooling to panels, which causes them to run hotter than equivalent panels at sea level under the same irradiance, increasing the temperature-derating effect. The net result is that Colorado Springs produces slightly more energy per rated watt than Denver (5,280 feet) and significantly more than sea-level markets at the same latitude.`,
    tariffPara: `CSU's $0.13/kWh rate is low, which extends solar payback to 9-12 years. CSU offers net metering for systems under 25kW at the retail rate with monthly rollover. The four-service municipal utility structure means CSU sets its own solar policy without PUC oversight, which has historically been moderately solar-friendly. CSU's low rate means the dollar value per kWh of solar production is lower than high-rate markets, making the economics less compelling than California or Northeast markets. For homeowners with above-average consumption (military families in large homes, EV charging, pool/spa equipment), the math improves because the system displaces more absolute dollars.`,
